node.text: When I started @projecthiu I didn't care about humans, I cared about sharks. I planned manipulation more than I did collaboration. I knew it would make life a bit better for them in the process to transition them from fishing to tourism, but they weren't my reason for being here, sharks were. And slowly... my focus has become equally about people, as it has sharks. Realising their choice to fish them is not a choice, that this is all they have to feed their kids, that my assumption of who they were as people was wrong. As evidenced from my time with them, and moments like the ones in these clips, they are good men, family men. I want to change their occupation to save sharks, just as much as I want to do it to save them from the negative sides of fishing. Isn't it funny, I came here to teach the shark fishermen how to be better people, turns out I was the one who needed to be a better person. I had it all wrong, and @projecthiu has been a product of me trying to make it right.

(🚨ANNOUNCMENT) – A very generous Crew Member has decided to donate a pre-paid set of Origin fins, dive mask and waterproof back pack to one lucky winner. We are so thankful for all the support shown since the founding of our project and we can’t wait to give back, terima kasih. (Winner drawn within next 24hrs). 

How to enter: Share this video message on your IG story and tag @projecthiu 

Changing the world by understanding someone else's, are the founding principles Project Hiu was built upon. Since we started, we've managed to transition a small part of this fishing community into tourism. Providing alternative incomes through utilising the very boats once used to fish sharks, changing the relationship and perception of how replenishing our oceans and showcasing its resources offers far greater financial returns in both the short and long term. The stories of these individuals are not that of villains, but people just trying to feed their families. By joining our Crew you will become responsible for altering the trajectory and perspective of a community and species that’s been exploited for generations, it’s time we change this. 

We are here to improve livelihoods above and below the surface and make no mistake, we’re not teaching them how to save the world, they are teaching us.

Footage in this little video captured by @caraghcreative @jackson.groves @naomiadbib @hunterghelton @mai.roper @b3njaminhall and audio from an interview with @gemma_care

Covid-19 means I didn't get to finish this film in the form I wanted, so I give you my first venture into talking to camera about my findings. In one of the most intense, hostile environments I have ever been in, being a recognizable “greenie” documenting some of this footage was scary. The main purpose of this short reel is to shed some light on the most dangerous part of this competition, the meat. Two samples of shark caught during this competition in New Jersey were taken and tested for mercury and both tested well over the safe limit as set by the FDA. I want to make it clear that I respect a lot of recreational shark fishermen, a lot are involved in conservation and demonstrate deep respect for the animal and desire to see them flourish in the future, but none of this was reflected in the men engaging in these competitions. Now is the time, as a community, we raise the standard for the treatment of wild apex predators and change the way we see this recreation. As the ocean changes, so must we.
Spoiler alert;
I tested a blue shark and a thresher shark for mercury. Both samples highly exceeded safe and legal limits. 
This film was made possible but @joeromeiro333 and @briannepowers who helped me gather this footage!

node.text: I followed these stunning sharks for ages, watching them move in precision following oil coming from the dead whale.  Australia is full of wild animals and despite this the only thing most people share with them is proximity. Knowledge, respect and information on dangerous marine life needs to become part of our curriculum in schools and general knowledge for adults. People were surfing near this whale with little concept of the danger and our reaction to shark attacks leads to shark deaths. Ineffective cull and in discriminatory nets plague our wildlife because of our fear. No one is reporting on this whale as a warning for surfers. Download everything you need to know about sharks before surfing with them here. www.surfingguidetosharks.com So lucky to have filmed these amazing creatures descend on this whale. @panamunaproject @projecthiu @wsl @envoy.film

node.text: I started project Hiu with @markewang and the help of @australiangeographic without any idea it would work. It was simple in my mind, we would stop these men fishing sharks if we could provide them with an alternative source of income, employ them in tourism. Everyone has a family they are trying to feed. So how do you end generations of fishing sharks? You don’t. You replace it. So that's what I did, convincing my first fisherman to join me which lead to six boats joining me. They make double what they would fishing sharks in tourism and  don't have to leave their families. What if we improve life below, by improving life above. It took me more than a year to know these fishermen. To eat with them, travel with them, meet their families, work with them. It took time and patience and a lot of trust. Some of us are of conservationists because we can afford to be, and some of us are shark fishermen because we can’t afford not to be. To be effective sometimes you have to put aside your how things make you feel, you have to see the bigger picture which serves no person purpose or gain to ones own emotions, but can eventually lead to what the world needs, effective change and collaboration with our so called enemies to inflict that change. We are constantly growing and changing and learning and depending on your support @projecthiu #projecthiu stay updated for trip dates, join me in Indonesia. Footage by @caraghcreative @jackson.groves @benhallx @hunterghelton @galen.neil

node.text:
There are a few things i’d like you to know about the shark fin trade.
1. Hong Kong and Guangzhou, mainland China, are the largest shark fin markets and consumption centers in the world. Shark fin soup represents a high status in society despite having no taste or medical benefits.
2. Demand is real. My friend is a scientist who bases himself in Hong Kong for months at a time to collect samples for genetics testing, he told me often they have none to buy, because the fin trimmings sell out so fast. 
3. In 2008, the world's top exporters of shark fins were Spain, Singapore, Taiwan, Indonesia and United Arab Emirates.
4. The men who kill these sharks have no idea how much fins are sold for. Which means they are unaware that the “good” money they are making from fishing sharks is actually exploitation at it’s finest as the fins are being marked up so severely when they reach Hong Kong.
5. Protected species laws and CITES is not a bulletproof solution. The trading of protected animals often goes on with little ability to enforce it and loopholes. 
6. Shark fins are toxic. A new study has found that most processed shark fins have mercury and methyl-mercury levels five to 10 times higher than the legal maximum amount of 0.5 parts per million, as specified by the Centre for Food Safety (CFS) in Hong Kong. A neuroticism called BMAA linked to neurodegenerative diseases in humans including Alzheimer's and Lou Gehrig Disease (ALS) has also been found in shark fins. 
7. Some of the best activists advocating for the end of shark fin soup consumption are Chinese, so there is no room for racism. 
The fin I’m holding in this photo belongs to a bigeye thresher shark. The market where it’s being processed is where I met the men I now employ in tourism. The shark fin trade was the pandemic that took down the shark, infecting the most isolated regions of the world to supply an increasing demand for shark fin soup. To this day, it remains a force that will eliminate the shark if we allow it. 📷 @caraghcreative and please follow @hongkongsharkfoundation to follow important work.
A shift in reality for me. Like seeing old friends where they belong. 📷 @tannerunderwater @caraghcreative thank you @discoversharkstours @discoversharks #maldives

node.text: I was lucky as a kid, I grew up playing with sharks. When you are raised with something it shapes you... then it's disappearance devastates you. I didn't just spend the last three months in Indonesia document the shark fin trade, I spent it with the men responsible. Growing closer to them, closer to the cause, closer to having an impact one day. My time in Indonesia has come to an end and I need to thank everyone that's supported me while I've been there. Thank you for donating, for sending encouraging messages. Thank you to the fishermen I now call family. Thank you for your support that allows us to make a difference here. Life's changed since I was a kid, scenes like this are common now. They push me to fight harder, you don't learn to live with them, you fight to change them. A special thank you to the following people who made it possible for me to be here for @projecthiu  thank you @convowithryan @bryndabella @sunbutterskincare @caraghcreative @3enhall @connortrimble

node.text: Don’t make the mistake of thinking @projecthiu is about "educating fishermen". My captain speaks four languages, I only speak one. It’s not a case of lack of education, it’s my reach and place of privilege, allowing who they already are and what they already know to be used for good. After fishing with them at sea for two weeks, living with them and watching their children grow, if anyone has been educated here... it's me. The concept of befriending your enemies never made sense to me, now my best friends are shark fishermen. The best men I know. 📷 @caraghcreative @projecthiu

node.text: The Bowmouth. Scientific name, Rhina ancylostoma. I saw one diving when I was young at about 30 meters off a reef wall in Micronesia. I had no idea what I was looking at, strangest creature I've ever seen. Now I've seen two dead. They are prehistoric looking, critically endangered, and have highly valued fins because of their distinctive spots. They are considered by some scientists to be the ‘missing link’ between sharks and rays based on the ray-like placement of the mouth and gill openings, and disc shape of the front part of the body and the shark-like streamlined appearance of the rest of the body and the powerful tail. I've become accustomed to seeing things here in the market that I will not see again in the wild. It's a reality I don't want to be accustomed to. 📷 @caraghcreative @projecthiu

node.text: The further away I flew the more levels of drying fins are exposed. I followed a lead, I took a risk, three cancelled flights and too many PCR tests and many failed attempts to chase this lead. I was close to giving up then I spotted them. I rushed some shots at risk of being seen or caught. This is one of one of many export factories in Indonesia where shark fins are prepared, marked up and sold. These could be the sharks I stood amongst last week but this is where it gets dangerous, this is where money, police and corruption is involved. This is a tiny example of the scale things can get, two levels of fins. Project Hiu has always had a really good and humbling presence as a small attempt to make a difference to lives of individuals at the source. The truth, it goes deeper. I've got a scary chain to unravel, a massive trade that acts like an infection on the developing parts of the world. The #sharkfin trade is what drives the men I work with, so I need to understand it. Isn't it amazing, that money isn't just enough to drive certain animals to extinction in this world, but for us to completely disregard the safety of other humans. The shark fins here represent more than a disgusting act against nature, but a massive neglect of our own kind. Each one belonging to an animal significantly impacting an ecosystem that provides indoensian communities with 60% of their diet, and representing a dangerous two week trip for a mere $150AUD for the fishermen involved. Each fin is a crime against human and shark alike. If we have to push boundaries to expose that, so be it. The film SHARKWATER really pioneered these shots, times where Rob climbed onto the roof to film shark fins like these drying. in many ways it felt like Rob was watching over my shoulder in this moment. #sharkfin #sharkfinsoup #savesharks
